,Recommended,239120,14492870,"Posted: 15 February, 2015",all,Sivek,"Just to start off, if you're looking at this game as a potential gateway to getting into traditional JRPG's, don't bother.  It will only serve to put you off the genre all together.  There are just too many things, like lack of save points and some cheap bosses, for someone that may want to play a more old-school game and is looking at FFIII, the earliest available FF game on Steam, as the game to start out with.That said, if you've played a lot of old RPG's growing up, you may find something more to your liking here.  The story and characters are simple.  There's no voice acting, no FMV cutscenes, no minimap or compass to point you in the right direction.  I found all of the above a benefit to the game.  The story parts would be slowed down by voice acting and the generic story would be exposed further if you had to listen to it and instead of just reading text.  While the game is fairly linear, it does a great job at points of making you wonder where to go and there's a real sense of exploration.  There's like five or more villages you don't ever have to go to for any reason that are just there, and despite them being pretty small, it's a cool little thing that you'd never see in a more modern game.The big thing with this game is that in was the introduction of the job-swapping system found in the earlier FF's.  There are twenty plus jobs and they're handed out at set points in the story.  The big problem is the last set of jobs are unlocked extremely late in the game and this makes using them to their fullest a pain.  You can switch jobs on the fly but there's a small penalty to stats for x amount of fights.  It's not a big deal and will only hamper you for a handful of random battles.The big downside to the game is complete lack of effort when redesigning the boss encounters and the final dungeon in its entirety.  Every boss fight boils down to the same thing.  A single enemy will have a strong physical attack that hits one character and strong magic attacks that hits everyone.  Bosses will also always use these attacks back to back without interruption.  This means any character, even with full HP, is liable to get KO'd if they get RNG unlucky when it comes to boss turns versus your characters' turns.  It's such a cheap, low-effort way to add difficulty when designing bosses.  Every turn of every boss fight eventually winds up with you casting a group heal spell on an already fully healed group just to deal with the oncoming attacks.The last dungeon and it's surroundings is one of the worst in RPG's and I'm sure you can find detailed reasons why elsewhere.There's a lot of talk about grinding being necessary in this game and I find that completely overblown.  I never stopped my progress for the explicit grinding of levels/ job levels and beat the game with levels in the very low 50's.  Grinding some levels would have helped for the last boss to serve as an HP buffer but it's not necessary.  As long as you don't continuously change your jobs, you should be able to handle anything the game can throw at you as long you fight every random encounter you come across.  The secret boss though would require a ton, and I mean a ton, of grinding and I didn't bother with it.As for the port, it's a super low effort one of the mobile version, not the DS version.  This means stuff like the UI is ugly and created to be touch based, but lacking in touch suport or mouse control in menus in this version and is just poor all around.  Even things like loading your game while in-game is obtuse.  There are only three save slots for who knows what reason.  I also ran into a problem where all dialogue box text had some type of artifacting or something that I couldn't find a work around for.  All that said, it's still supposedly better the FFIV PC port, which doesn't even have the memorize battle cursor function because it wasn't included in the mobile version and has 15 FPS in battles.  I used the memorize function in FFIII so I'll be missing it when I eventually get around to playing FFIV.  Square just doesn't give a♥♥♥♥♥♥with any of their PC ports so none of this should be a surprise.Okay, since this was really long, here's a short answer as to whether you should buy and play this game.  Don't if you have no experience with older RPG's.  If you do and are fine with not having things like save points and easily obtainable reviving items, cheap bosses and a terrible final dungeon, you'd probably get some enjoyment out of FFIII.  It's an enjoyable, but clearly flawed game."
,Recommended,239120,10403167,"Posted: 8 June, 2014",all,Jedo,"FF3 is a decent fantasy rpg that features a short and straightforward plotline. It boasts numerous job choices and combinations similar to its NES counterpart and the tactics series.This game is of course not without drawbacks. Among other titles in the FF series, I would rank this as slightly  above average due to one or two missing (but important) features.The game does not have an option to adjust battle speed. This was something you could find in FF games of previous generations so it's a shame that this isn't built into the PC port of the game. Keep in mind that there's an achievement for getting all jobs to level 99 which will require a minimum of 2254 battles (that's if you're super efficient) so this particular option would have been a godsend.Content-wise, I also feel that it is below/lacking in comparison to the 2 other games which are also on Steam. This is purely subjective but I feel that the price point needs to be adjusted after considering this factor. It's a shame because the game ends before it truly begins. You get your last set of jobs way too close to the end of the game.Despite these criticisms, I can still recommend FF3. It follows a nostalgic formula that most of the other games in the series observe. The game is especially good if you are a modern gamer who missed out on the treasured experience of playing the first half of the series."
76561197960450124,Recommended,239120,21824718,"Posted: 13 March, 2016",all,JohnnyDemo,"This game is an excellent old school Rpg, emphasis on the old school. Remember this game was orginally released April 1990 ( in Japan only), to put that in perspective it, Final Fantasy 1 came out for the NES in America that year! This version is a direct port of the DS version, which updated the graphics to a 3D engine.There is very little hand holding, often you will find yourself on the world map trying to remember a single line of dialogue from an NPC that will direct you. While the flow of the game is pretty good, there is a few times that you will need to grind out levels (and Job levels). Again, part of the old school feeling of this game.The Job system works for the most part and is designed to suit individual playstyles. Unfortunately there is many bosses that die easier to certain group make-ups. This can be a frustrating thing. Also a few of the jobs are direct upgrades from other jobs (white mage / devout or Monk / Black belt) rendering the previous job basically  obsolete.GraphicsWell not the best looking game the graphics do a servicable job. This will not put your system to the test that is for sure!SoundThe music and sound effects are pretty good and definitely have that ""final fantasy"" feel.StoryAs mentioned above the flow of the game is ok, but you do find yourself at certain points wondering where to go next (at least I did, anyway). Revisiting a couple of towns and talking to everyone may refresh the memory.GameplayOld school! Grinding levels although arguably not required is recommended. The Job levels have a different leveling system, as in they don't level up using Experience points. There is a hidden job point system that sets your levels. To accumulate these job points you perform actions in battle (attack, guard, item, magic etc.)  When JP is accumulated to 99, Job level goes up by 1. Each action (except: Front, Back, Escape, and Flee) will contribute a fixed amount of job points to the character.My only real complaint is when entering a battle the camera system often scrolls through the enemies. Really it comes down to like 3 seconds but when you're grinding levels it makes each battle longer than maybe it should be, this adds up over time. Again, just a very small gripe.There is very large portion of the game at the end where you are unable to save. Although I was lucky and got through it all unscathed, I can imagine the frustration of dieing and losing everything after sinking a couple of hours into the dungeon. Save and save often! Even if you don't think you need to!Overall I recommend this game especially if you're into Jrpg, and specifically ones from the past! :)8/10"
,Recommended,239120,16850286,"Posted: 2 July, 2015",all,Terrean,"Good remake of an old favorite.Pros- Job system is interesting with lots of options- Decent amount of grind v. story.  Lots of opportunity to max everything though if that's your thing- Bosses and new mobs can pose a threat- Finishing a job gets you a legendary item for that classCons- Some jobs are worthless- Zero description of Job Points - had to read a guide- Fastest way to level a job?  Just have all your guys Guard 7 times for an automatic job level at the end of the fight.  Should have been based on job special skills - Knights using Defend, Thief using Steal, mages using magic for the biggest boost, medium boost for normal actions like attacking, and very little for using items (unless Scholar) or Guarding.  I've maxed out a lot of the FF games and couldn't force myself to do it here.- Low agility characters/jobs end up at a disadvantage if you don't use the Guard method of job leveling.  They don't get to take an action and thus level slower than everyone else.- Legendary smith - difficult to access without looking at a guide, pops up in random places causing you to fly between two cities until she shows up at just to get your new job weapon, etc.  Poorly conceived.- Nothing carries over when you switch jobs.  It would be nice to keep some residual stats - Knight to White Mage should keep a little defense or vitality.- Save issue during the last boss.  Fight through a dungeon, fight boss, no save option except for quick save (does not allow you to resume there if you die).  Can't teleport or travel back to world map for a full save.  Enter final dungeon - if you happen to approach the final boss first like I did, you're screwed and you get one shotted meaning you lose about 20 minutes of progress and have to watch some really long cutsceens again.All in all, glad I picked it up on sale and got to see what they did with the remake."
,Recommended,239120,10255529,"Posted: 27 May, 2014",all,TheSinnersCreed,"So, I decided to dress up my review to make it easier to read as its a bit cluttered. As a long time fan of the Final Fantasy Series, I didn't get a chance to play FFIII till way later on an Emulator program on my PC. While I liked it immediately I lost interest after a few days because of the NES styled graphics.  With THIS release, however, the modern player will have a more enjoyable experience than with previous installments. It has improved graphics (well, DS level but definitely better than the NES), monsters are animated, music is a bit less annoying than the .midi's use to be and the way the cutscenes play out are vastly improved over their original versions.FFIII is the story of the Onion Knight, the reimergance of the Warriors of Light and the birth of Final Fantasy's Job Class System. The story is good, although the cast seems a bit ""thrown together"", it's really the mechanics and nostalgia that makes FFIII worth the buy. Random battles, old fashioned grinding (yes, it was popular before WoW and EQ) and FF canon like Moogles (Complete with a lackluster MogNet), Chocobo's, everyones favorite Mechanic / Airship Captain; Cid and the oddest overworld map on any FF game, ever.Overall, even as a slight fan of Mystic Quest (loved the dungeon music) and with my distaste with FFII and XI, FIII still maintains its place HIGH on my list of favoritsm for the FF Franchise. Although, FFIV will always be my favorite of the older series and XIII for the later series. If you've never played it yet but are a fan of the series, a young'un wanting a taste of nostalgic old school gaming or just someone with $15 to blow; come and relive a classic and get ready to have the level up theme stuck in your head for weeks!Kupo, Kupo and Game on!"
