76561198076698548,Not Recommended,239120,10265882,"Posted: 28 May, 2014",all,Sam Malone,"* Started game and everything was zoomed in no matter what resolution was set.  Zoomed in so far that all you could see was the top, left quadrant of the actual image.  Game is so new that there was no troubleshooting help online.  I had to scan through 20 + reviews and forum pages just to find mention of this issue.---------*** SOLUTION For those of you with the same experience***---------*  Select the FF3.exe file in your steamapps folder.* Right-Click on .exe and select 'Compatibilty'* Now selct the compatibility tab from this window* Toggle the 'disable DPI' setting..... The reason you are having this issue is because you are using a monitor that displays very high DPI.  I'm currently using Apple's Retna display and that is the highest DPI you can get right now besides 4k stuff.  But any monitor capiable of displaying over 1080p will most likley fall in this category.* The only other problem I experienced was a slight gamepad issue where my character wouldn't stop traveling west no matter what I did on the gamepad.  Unfortunatley, travelling west on the world map made me bump into a few mobs that I wasn't geared or leveled for, I died and then was sent back to my original save point which was signicantly far back in my game play.  This really♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥me off--- so I restarted and everything was fine.  If it happens again, I'll simply unplug the controller in hopes that will make it forget the error.Besides those 2 experiences, I would say that I am loving the game.  I never played the DS version nor did have I ever played any ports besides those awful ones for psx from the late 90s.  The game looks so beautiful now that it has been upscaled for PC and looks even better on my 50"" display (sitting 10 feet back of course).I really wanted to give a good review since FF are my favorite games, but unfortunately this PC release came out in 2014 and none of these issues should even exisit in the first place.  High DPI monitors are the future and no game should ever make you have to troubleshoot to find out that it is something this simple.  This game should be patched to auto-detect high DPI displays and allow users first time experience to be a plug n play situation like advertized.SQUARE:  PLEASE KEEP THE FF REMAKES COMING, JUST DO A BETTER JOB AT LAUNCH!! TAKE MY MONEY PLEASE!!"
,Recommended,239120,31379646,Posted: 26 April,all,Zero Summ,"Pros:It's a classic.Great soundtrack.Port of the DS/Android version of FF3. I didn't run into any bugs in the 40+ hours I put into it.Gampad support.Neutral:Launcher. It's not a huge deal but I'm kind of disappointed that they didn't just integrate the settings into the game itself. If you want to alter things like resolution or game-pad configuration you'll need to close down your game and change it in the launcher.Lack of a simple tutorial. I'm all for games not holding your hand, but they don't even explain simple mechanics. It took me like 10 hours before I got frustrated enough to go and Google how to use spells on equipped weapons. (You have to press up while you're inside the item menu if you're wondering.)Achievements are outrageously grindy. I realize you don't need to do them, but getting all jobs on all characters to 99 is just insane.Cons:While some see a classic, others will see an outdated game. Combat is very simple, and the storyline is shallow and cliché.If your controller disconnects during play, you'll need to restart your game in order for it to work again.Lack of save points near the end of the game."
,Recommended,239120,15716594,"Posted: 6 May, 2015",all,Wellbien,"Pure, unspoiled Final Fantasy at its best.I first played this game back in 2006 when it was introduced stateside to the Nintendo DS and I loved every freaking minute of it. Final Fantasy III is a sweet, charming, and satisfying Final Fantasy experience. The style of the music, the artwork, and the feel of the game has yet to be replicated.Luneth, Arc, Inguis, and Refia are four adventurers who become the Warriors of Light. Their roles in the party are based on which jobs you assign to them that unlock as you progress through the story. The story is simple but engaging enough to want to see through to the end.This game is HARD, especially when you're used to the more modern FF titles. I can't sugarcoat the difficulty at all. You will rarely get a phoenix down, so trips back to town to revive fallen party members may happen frequently. If you are looking for a challenge, you will certainly find it here.It's kinda sad that it took over a decade for this gem to see a US release, but it has already taken place as one of my favorite games of all time and one of my favorite FF titles. Completing this game is one of the most rewarding experiences ever. I recommend getting both FF3 and FF4 on Steam as both are challenging in their own ways but offer different experiences."
