,Recommended,239120,20797172,"Posted: 27 January, 2016",all,Flonn,"While it is a port of the DS remake, it has enough of the simplicity and that grindy flavor to hit the spot for that early Final Fantasy JRPG nostalgia (note: I've experienced no issues with the port).Much of this is owed to the fact that this game is almost a verbatim remake, which reflects the restrictions of the ancient technology of 1990, when the game was first released. The redsign of the game was primarily only a visual & audio makeover (updated music, '3D' environments & sprites, etc). The gameplay and construction are almost identical to the original.This means that there really isn't much at all to the story, and the characters are pretty much completely flat. So if you're expecting the rich development you'd find in the story and characters of the later installments in the series (pretty much any of them after this one), look elsewhere.Further, the maps used in the original games have been retained here - and that includes the limitations in design, as  So, similar to the limited story, dialogue, and characters, you'll find that they're disappointingly simple.While all the above might seem like a pile of complaints, it's actually not. What has been redone, has been redone well. The visuals are limited to that of a DS, however im finding that the music is really enjoyable. All in all, it's been a fun experience - just don't expect this to compare to the modern (high-budget) maserpieces that the Series produces.Bottom line: if you're looking for a nostalgic feel with a bit of modern flavor, this just might hit the spot."
76561198088380930,Recommended,239120,34563341,Posted: 28 August,all,emasterslake,"Final Fantasy III was originally released in the year 1990 and was the last Final Fantasy title to be released on the Nintendo Entertainment System. It was among the three canon Final Fantasy titles to previously not get a domestic release in America. Not until 16 years later when a remake was made for the Nintendo DS. And this is what this game is, a PC port of the Nintendo DS remake. While it would of been cool to play the original version of the game, it unfornately was never given a release outside of Japan. So for the time being, this is the only version of Final Fantasy III, we may be able to play unless you buy the game directly from Japan, played the unofficial English port, or someone strikes a deal with Square-Enix. Like how Final Fantasy II was finally released domestically as part of the Final Fantasy Origins game for Playstation and the previously unreleased Final Fantasy V got a domestic release as well. With the conclusion of that history lecture, let me review Final Fantasy III. The game takes place on a floating continent that is seperated from the world below due to a flood that occured a millineum ago. Four young orphans named Luneth, Arc, Refia, & Ingus learn from a magical crystal that laid dormint in a newly opened cave that they are the Warriors of Lights are prophecied in legend. The four orphans are the floating continent and the old world's only hope in restoring balance of peace from the newly ressurected dark forces that threaten to consume the rest of the world and the population with enternal darkness. This was a fun game and offered the same appeal as found in Final Fantasys I & II. This was the first game in the series to have the main protagnogists as kids, as the original game the age for the protagnogists was ambigous while the cast of the second game are young adult. This was the first in the series to offer the ""job"" option where the four orphans can be assigned to a different role like a mage, monk, knight, summoner, etc. Each job gives a character different abilities or different items to use. Longer you fight against monsters with each assigned job, the more experienced the character is with that job title. This task is a nessecity in order to progress in the game. While the leveling system was reverted back to a simple experience point gain system as oppose to the more complex level system in Final Fantasy II, so leveling up your characters is easier this time around. The moogles and fat chobos make their debut in this game, as well as the first time the main characters can summon creatures, deities, and mosnters during the battle sequences. Any one who is a die hard Final Fantasy or RPG fan will enjoy what this game has to offer. It may not be the 1990 Final Fantasy III, but it is a great alternative to play and is currently the oldest numeric Final Fantasy title to play from Steam."
