,Recommended,239120,10317357,"Posted: 1 June, 2014",all,Warp,"Final Fantasy III (the original Japanese one, not FF6 which was unfortunately named ""FF3"" in its original western release)... There isn't much to say about the game itself that hasn't been said a million times during the decades. Solid early Square JRPG, originally for the NES. If you liked FF1 and 2, this is pretty much a sure bet. (This revamp of the game is also nice because the original FF3 was never exported back in the day, so not many people got to play it.)The graphical upgrade is interesting. They could have gone the same route as with what they did with FF1 and FF2 when they remade them for the PSP and DS, iow. keep it 2D, just with modern graphics. Instead of that, they chose simplistic PlayStation1-style ""retro-3D"" graphics. This was an interesting choice, and it works. It brings the extra depth that 3D provides (in more senses than just the added third dimension), but still manages to keep a nostalgic ""retro"" feeling to it. They could have botched it up, but it works fine.For someone who has never played JRPGs, and especially someone who has only played modern games, the visuals and gameplay may feel appalling at first. The game may feel extremely simplistic, even boring, both from a visual and a gameplay perspective. However, if you give it a chance, I'm sure that you'll end up loving it. (And of course if you are a long-time old gamer like me, you'll probably love it right away.)Works very well with an Xbox360 controller out-of-the-box (although the in-game hints always refer to the keyboard keys, so you have to sometimes find the buttons by trial-and-error.)"
