,Recommended,239120,11549899,"Posted: 4 August, 2014",all,Face Hugger,"One of the games in the series that wasn't originally published in the US. FF III Introduces the job system - a staple in later games in the series. A fair remake of an 8-bit game, with updated polygonal graphics (a port of the Nintendo DS version), modern audio, animated cut scenes, and illustrated character profiles. There are some heldover design relics though - such as a clunky interface and useless quick save system (quick saves are not persistent).As brutal as any early Final Fantasy game if one does not know where to go for leveling. The challenge makes for rewarding advancement. Exploration is encouraged, even backtracking over previously cleared areas can reveal new items. Classic Final Fantasy turn-based combat, and the kind of whimsical story telling you're probably expecting."
,Not Recommended,239120,23826618,"Posted: 26 June, 2016",all,Alucard,"Ah, FFIII. Originally released on the Famicom only in Japan, which caused quite a lot of confusion with the numbering, this is the last Final Fantasy (or at least the last numbered one) made for the third generation of gaming (NES/Sega Master System). After a 3D remake on the DS and a few ports later, it's finally on Steam.Unfortunately, this remake is *too* faithful, and it doesn't quite hold up. There's no real sense of direction after the first dungeon, which you are dropped in straight away (literally). *SPOILERS* After you deal with a few random encounters and beat the boss, a crystal talks to you, and you appear on the overworld. You go to your town, watch a friend get bullied and then run off, talk to the village elders who basically say, ""You have been chosen since birth by the crystals! It was no coincidence that it spoke to you now! Oh, and by the way, you're adopted!"" (I kid you not, they flat out tell your character that he's adopted, and he has no reaction to that. It's not even because he's a silent protag, he just doesn't say anything back)*SPOILERS END*Unlike the FFIV DS remake, there are no thought bubbles that appear when you use your menu on the world map, which would add some character to the otherwise stereotypical characters. You have your flat, adventurous main character, his best friend, a random girl you meet on an airship, and a castle guard. By the way, they're all 14 for whatever reason, even the castle guard, and they all look like they could be older. Don't expect the rest of the game to be any less cliche.The OST is nice, I suppose. The standard town and battle music is good, but not great. The music for the Sealed Cave, the first dungeon, is...interesting. It's good, but it's not really what I would've expected for the first non-tutorial dungeon. I especially like ""Into the Crystal Cave"", as well as ""Eternal Wind"", and ""Jinn's Curse"", and that's all that I've liked from what I've heard so far.The plot is slightly more complex than Final Fantasy I in that your characters actually speak and have...well...character! The plot is still plastic, and you still have to go on a cliche fetch quest for crystals after being declared the chosen ones, though. Also, *MINOR SPOILERS* you get an airship not even an hour into the game, which seems odd to me. I thought airships were things you got in the middle of the game, not right at the beginning with no effort. I'm not sure if I'm upset about it, because on one hand you get to experience the freedom of flight earlier, and on the other hand it cheapens the concept of getting an airship.*MINOR SPOILERS OVER*The visuals are probably the best part about this game. The chibi style and colorful palette makes the world seem inviting and playful, which is probably the only reason I even played more after I got out of the tutorial dungeon. In this case, the graphics did make the game for me.The gameplay, like the plot, is only slightly more complex than Final Fantasy I's. If you've played FFI, you know that if you make all your characters attack one enemy and the first hit or so kills it, the rest of your attacks will be ""ineffective"", because their target is already dead. This is the first game to fix that, and it does so by automatically selecting a new target for a given character's attack. Brilliant, right? Still, because this is FFIII and not FFIV, there is no ATB, which means that instead of a gauge filling up for a given character so they can attack, you just select new commands at the end of each ""turn"", like Pokemon. However, Pokemon has several type advantages and disadvantages, 4 moves per Pokemon, and loads of other things to make the combat more complex, while FFIII just has your choice of weapons, and I suppose a unique ability here and there when you meet more playable characters. Sure, the elemental black magic will be more effective against certain types, but it's still not the same complexity as in Pokemon, and even then, not everyone has black magic (although there is a way to give everyone black magic, but it's not worth it). For an apt analogy concerning FFIII's combat compared to FFIV's, think of coaching a football/soccer/other sport game vs. playing in one. FFIII is where you coach.Oh, still on the topic of combat, sometimes enemies are faster than you, sometimes you're faster than them. It doesn't even seen to be a constant thing during the same battle, and so it can't possibly be due to different enemies being different levels even though they're the same type of enemy. This pretty much makes any strategy impossible to rely on 100%, which means straight up luck is now a factor. I suppose luck is also a factor in real life combat, but this isn't real life. When you get to the first actual dungeon, prepare to get destroyed if you didn't grind a lot beforehand. Yeah, it's one of those RPGs.Should FFIII have stayed in Japan? Nah. While I bash on it quite a bit in this review, it's great to look at how far the franchise has come. Gotta have bad games to appreciate good ones, and all. Still, I can't in good faith recommend this to anyone, or at least this version, RPG lover or not. I hear the PSP version is the best, but I have not played much of it despite owning it. I'll update this review if/when I bring myself to play more of this version, but for now, I must give it the thumbs down."
,Not Recommended,239120,17188315,"Posted: 23 July, 2015",all,McGamer,"Even thou this game is a revamp I won't recommend it. Yeah sure it's an FF game but, I'm quite disappointed if you screw up you just have to start over from the beginning if your characters dies at a certain point 'game over'.Thief is pretty much a must just to get some phoenix down without them you are pretty much screwed.I do enjoy the FF series otherwise, but come on this is lame!"
