,Recommended,239120,15707713,"Posted: 5 May, 2015",all,goblin girl,"I think I'm kinda seeing why this game took so long to be ported.Final Fantasy III is by no means the weakest in the series. (II is worse, and there's that one later entry ... we both know which one). The combat system makes sense, the Jobs mostly make sense, and there's a forward-moving plot.Thing is, though ... it's not very interesting. It's really mostly just a selection of classic Final Fantasy tropes shuffled together and re-dealt. There's the Job system, the familiar list of spells, dungeons, the airship, elemental crystals, etc., etc., etc. It's true that some of these things actually originated here, but it kind of doesn't help? When I go back to FF1 I can see it's retro and primitive but it still has a ""freshness"" to it that FF3 lacks.All I know is, if I'm in the mood to replay a retro Final Fantasy that evokes all the old tropes like this, I'm more likely to go to FF5 for its more intricate plot and less bland characters.That said, I mean, there's nothing really WRONG here. There's nothing wrong with a bread-and-butter sandwich or a glass of plain water ... I was just kind of really hoping for a grilled cheese and Coke, y'know? So while I'm recommending the game, I'm probably not going to be playing it through more than once, ever."
76561198022306820,Recommended,239120,16070049,"Posted: 29 May, 2015",all,Guardic,"As a game, this game is very fun and challenging. As a Final Fantasy, it's not the best in the series, but it's definitely better than anything after Final Fantasy IX (except Final Fantasy XII). I'm not sure why everyone keeps complaining about bugs, but I've never seen a single one through either of my playthroughs. The only real complaint I have with the game is the fact that to level up your jobs, you have to perform an action (fight, guard or an ability) to gain job points (which is a hidden stat) In Final Fantasy V or even Final Fantasy Tactics, you received job points after each battle or kill that went towards leveling your job.Also, your HP gain is based on what job class you have equipped when you get a character level up. So if you keep one character as a magic user the whole game, they will end up with low HP by the end, which in turn causes A LOT of extra grinding as a job you really don't want to use. Even still, the HP gain system in this Final Fantasy is strange. At level 60 on my first playthrough, I had about 3500 HP with each character, giver or take. Which made some boss battles aggravating since bosses tend to hit VERY hard with physical attacks but not so much with magic. In conclusion, it's definitely worth the money if you're a Final Fantasy fan, a fan of games with a class based system (Might & Magic, Wizardry) or if your a fan of retro RPGs.7/10"
