,Recommended,239120,26453193,"Posted: 6 November, 2016",all,Joachim,"Final Fantasy III is an old school j-rpg with remade graphics. Recommending this game will depend on your ability to appreciate game design from the early 90s. To be more specific quest design, encounter design and story are all barebones.Quests consist of going somewhere, kill someone, get an object, advance. There are very few sidequests, and exploration is limited due to the size of the world map and the convenience of transportation. That is not necessarily a flaw, as the game still has a good amount of content, and ends up more focused. Except at the end, you won't get lost or stumble in the wrong places, which comes at the price of fulfilling exploration.Level design abuses the use of secret corridors. Basically some corridors are hidden behind fake walls, and completely dark, so you have to stumble across them. Also you often have to backtrack if you want to get every nook and cranny. Other than that it's basic but effective. The encounters are repetitive and lack the needs of strategy to solve them, you basically brute force through everything, as you seldom run out of ressources if you are well prepared. With that said, they still are satisfying because you can't save in dungeons, and as you advance the tension rises. That is, if you go into dungeons casually and unprepared, because otherwise the game becomes a cakewalk.The story is minimal, but like it's graphics it has a cutesy kind of charm. Characters have no development, the story bends to accomodate for the gameplay, if you rely on a good story to carry your experience you will find it severely lacking here and I would advise you against this game.Overall I found the game rewarding to finish, and I would recommend it on that ground. I like that you can choose whatever classes you like from a pool of 20+ jobs, I like the charming simplicity of this game, and I found it to be effective in what it sets to be. But I wouldn't recommend it for people who have modern standards, as the game clearly doesn't meet them."
