,Recommended,239120,26572057,"Posted: 12 November, 2016",all,Craigosaurusflex,"Great class system, typical FF Crystal story, hidden items and chest, a bit of grind. Great for those looking for a classic JRPGStoryLike in the original Final Fantasy III you play as the four Onion Knights: Luneth, Arc, Refia and Butts. These guys were basically created to give the onion knights a sense of individual character and design. Anyway you start the story off with amnesia in typical JRPG fashion, you fight some monsters in a cave and then get told you're the chosen one. You gather your four party members within the first two-three hours and then you're off saving the flying continent from Xande using the power of the four crystals. The story is incredibly weak, but that's not why you're here.Battle Mechanics and GameplayDon't go into this expecting anything complex, it's a classic JRPG It uses a turn based system setup like so:AttackClass Abilities/MagicGuardItemsFlee (If available)Grinding isn't too necessary if you're not fleeing every encounter and if you have set strategies for the bosses, but this is only if you'e hunting hidden chests for hidden equipment. However grinding is incredibly viable if you're looking to 100% the game. Turns are purely based on characters attack speeds, there is no ATB in this game.SoundSoundtrack really isn't too memorable aside from the battle themes, chocobo theme and the dancer themes. Not muchChoice and FreedomsThis game boasts a unique 23 classes all with their own different playstyles, to go along with the boatload of classes to choose from you also have a heavy amount of character customization, classes are not limited to just one weapon type, you have access to over a hundred weapons and armor throughout the game. This game really treats you with the variety of equipment and class builds.Exploration in dungeons and the overworld will benefit you as you'll find alot of hidden loot, but the story progression is incredibly linear."
